<DOC><DOCNO> DOE1-61-0596 </DOCNO><TEXT>The child who comes to the hospital because of an abdominal mass entersa diagnostic maze surrounded by decision trees. In the last 8 years ultrasonographyhas been added to the array of sophisticated equipment that awaits thechild at every turn. This chapter is written as a guide to the use ofultrasound in the diagnosis of an abdominal mass in a child. It is basedon the authors' experience at Children's Hospital Medical Center (CHMC)over a period of 4 years, during which time 482 children were evaluated.The study was completed before the advent of computed tomography (CT)at the institution. Included in the discussion is a selective reviewof the literature dealing with the evaluation of an abdominal mass inthe pediatric patient.</TEXT></DOC>